{"key":"processedPost-14006116","value":{"id":14006116,"first":14006077,"last":14006744,"when":1298383510,"utime":"02/22/11 04:05 PM","content":"Not quite.&nbsp; Leave the stirrer on.&nbsp; The mycelium should be broken up with an eberbach and then put on LC if one chooses to go that route.&nbsp; However, making LC from spores is much slower than inoculating grains, and then doing grain to grain transfers.&nbsp; LC will also fail much more often and you have no way of knowing until you attempt to use it, several weeks down the road.&nbsp; The rest of us will be eating mushrooms before your LC is ready to use.<br />Liquid favors bacteria as anyone who has used a spore syringe to inoculate agar plates has found out.&nbsp; Squirting spores into sugar water has worse than a 50% failure rate, so I'm at a loss why people are still doing it.<br />RR","title":"Re: L.M.E. per X amount of water (pics)"}}